    "summary": "Alexander's Indian Campaign (327–325 BC) took his army into the Punjab region of northwestern India, the easternmost extension of [[event:75|Alexander the Great's Empire]] and the limit of any western conquest until the modern era. Crossing the Hindu Kush and the Khyber Pass, Alexander defeated the Indian king Porus at the [[event:1037|Battle of Hydaspes]] — the only battle in India that involved a pitched engagement against war elephants — and continued eastward with the intention of reaching the world's eastern ocean.\n\nThe campaign stalled on the banks of the Hyphasis (Beas) River, where Alexander's veterans, after eight years of continuous campaigning stretching from Macedonia to the Punjab, finally refused to advance further. Alexander reportedly wept and secluded himself in his tent for three days before accepting the army's decision. He turned south, leading the army through intense fighting in the Indus Valley, where he was nearly killed in the storming of a Malli town — an arrow pierced his lung, and his recovery was uncertain for days. The army then split: the fleet under Nearchus sailed the Indian Ocean coast toward the Persian Gulf while Alexander led the main body through the Gedrosian desert in an appallingly costly march that killed thousands. The Indian campaign's legacy included the [[event:1104|Indo-Greek Kingdom]] established by later Hellenistic kings in the region.",
